The `NullPointerException` you are encountering is due to the fact that you have declared an array of Query objects, but you haven&#39;t actually initialized the individual elements of the array. In Java, when you create an array of objects, each element of the array is initially null until you explicitly create instances of those objects using the new keyword.
You can modify the second for loop as
```
for (int i = 0; i &lt; m; i++) {
    q[i] = new Query(); // Initialize each Query object
    int L = sc.nextInt();
    int R = sc.nextInt();
    q[i].setQuery(i, L, R, L / sz);
}
```
In this code, I&#39;ve added the line `q[i] = new Query();` inside the loop where you are initializing your Query objects. This ensures that you create a new instance of the Query class for each element of the q array before calling the setQuery method.

