If you check your binding logic, you are checking for the boolean property and only prints the custom string when the boolean is false.

    targetProperty.bind(Bindings.when(booleanProperty)
                    .then(sb)
                    .otherwise(stringProperty));

So it doesn&#39;t bother about the stringProperty value as long as the booleanProperty is true.  You turned it to true, but never turned back to false. So you cannot expect the new string value.

To get it work as your expected output, you need to also turn the booleanProperty to false.

    booleanProperty.set(false); // You are missing this line
    stringProperty.set(&quot;Hello again&quot;);
    System.out.println(targetProperty.get());

Based on that expected output, you want a target property&#39;s value to be determined by one of two other properties, based on whichever of the other two properties was changed _last_. I would use listeners for that, not bindings.

```java
import javafx.beans.property.BooleanProperty;
import javafx.beans.property.SimpleBooleanProperty;
import javafx.beans.property.SimpleStringProperty;
import javafx.beans.property.StringProperty;

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        StringProperty sourceStr = new SimpleStringProperty();
        BooleanProperty sourceBool = new SimpleBooleanProperty();

        StringProperty targetStr = new SimpleStringProperty();
        sourceStr.addListener((obs, oldVal, newVal) -&gt; targetStr.set(newVal));
        sourceBool.addListener((obs, oldVal, newVal) -&gt; targetStr.set(&quot;boolean is &quot; + newVal));

        sourceStr.set(&quot;Hello&quot;);
        System.out.println(targetStr.get());

        sourceBool.set(true);
        System.out.println(targetStr.get());

        sourceStr.set(&quot;Hello again&quot;);
        System.out.println(targetStr.get());
    }
}
```

Output:

```none
Hello
boolean is true
Hello again
```

Though if you want to use bindings, you could always implement your own &quot;latest  of&quot; [`Binding`][1]&lt;sup&gt;**1**&lt;/sup&gt;.

---

&lt;sup&gt;**1.** I&#39;m not aware of any built-in API that can make this easier, other than [`ObservableValueBase`][2]. You could try to use something like `Bindings::createObjectBinding` or `ObjectBinding` directly, but neither gives you access to _which_ observable dependency was invalidated (unless you forgo the `bind` / `unbind` API of `ObjectBinding` and instead use your own listeners).&lt;/sup&gt;











  [1]: https://openjfx.io/javadoc/20/javafx.base/javafx/beans/binding/Binding.html
  [2]: https://openjfx.io/javadoc/20/javafx.base/javafx/beans/value/ObservableValueBase.html

