As you can see, I need access to the authenticated User to the WebSocket. 
According to the [documentation][1]

&gt; WebSockets reuse the same authentication information that is found in the HTTP request when the WebSocket connection was made.


And the problem is, while the WebSocket connection is open, the `User` information is likely to be changed. But, as the authentication information is from the HTTP request, that information could be outdated.

One solution is updating the `User` object used with the Repository, this way

    @MessageMapping(USER_LOCATION)
    public void sendLocation(@RequestBody Location location, Authentication authentication) {
        User user = (User)authentication.getPrincipal();
        user = USER_SERVICE.findById(user.getId()); // &lt;-- Repository updating
        LOCATION_SERVICE.sendUserLocation(user, location);
    }

But, this endpoint expects a big traffic, so that would traduce in a big amount of unnecessary database calls, reducing performance and increasing monetary cost.

Is there any way to update the `Authentication` object without acceding to the database every time that endpoint is called and accessing it only when the user is updated? 


## Why do I need this endpoint? ##

 My application has real-time location of each user. So, when any user opens the application the WebSocket connection is established and the client sends their location periodically (every 2 seconds). That location sending is not expected to finish until the user terminates the app. These locations are stored in a `HashMap` which acts like a buffer, where all the users and locations are stored:

    private final Map&lt;Long, UserLocation&gt; USER_LOCATION_BUFFER;

 When the client wants to access to the users in a specific location, access to that buffer. Not to the database.

 This buffer is modified with the method shown before `LOCATION_SERVICE.sendUserLocation()`, this way:

    public void sendUserLocation(User user, Location location) {
        USER_LOCATION_BUFFER.put(user.getId(), new UserLocation(user, location));
    }

 So, if in this time the user modify it&#39;s information (for example, changes their profile photo) the changes won&#39;t be shown to the other users until the user finishes the app and opens it again. Because the controller method `sendLocation` will override the user with the one which was established in the WebSocket connection.


## Is this a XY problem? ##
 According to what @JimGarrison proposed at the comments, this could be a [XY problem][2]. So, I&#39;m open to hear if I&#39;m facing the problem wrong. 

The decisiones that made me opt for this solutions were:

**I don&#39;t want to access to the database every time I have to retrieve a user from the buffer**
 
This is because this retrieving happens with very frequently (is also periodically) and it would traduce to a big amount of database calls and most of them unnecessary (exactly the same way as in my proposed solution). 

**The expected amount of users is not high**

This is not any surprise. As in any other new application, I aspire to start with a number of users in the order of thousands, if I&#39;m very lucky. So, I think that the cost (talking about RAM, price, etc.) of having that buffer, will be smaller than accessing to the database in every call.

  [1]: https://docs.spring.io/spring-security/reference/servlet/integrations/websocket.html
  [2]: https://xyproblem.info/

